Exposure and Infection

Modeling the PfEIR and the PfPR

November 09, 2023

~/Malaria Epidemiology/Malaria-Epidemiology.Rmd

HUB – Roadmap – Library – Malaria Epidemiology – Exposure – Scaling – Progressive Estimation

\(\odot\)

A core problem for malaria epidemiology is the relationship between exposure (i.e., as defined by the entomological inoculation rate or EIR) and infection (i.e. as defined by the prevalence of infection or PR). In the following document, we introduce a flexible mathematical framework for modeling exposure and infection, and we explore several factors affecting the scaling relationship. In this document, we use the cohort utilities in exDE to illustrate several factors that modify the scaling relationship between the EIR and the PR. In this document, we are taking an abstract, conceptual approach.

For RAMP, the big picture also involves an inferential process (see Fig. 1). In this document, we have not dealt with with either age or the observational process (i.e. sampling). We cover those topics more thoroughly in a synthesis of Scaling.

Figure 1: A core problem is to understand the intensity of malaria transmission by mosquitoes, which requires understanding the process of exposure and infection. This diagram illustrates how the RAMP algorithms deal with the relationship.

EIR-PR

\(\oplus\)

Exposure

  • Exposure risk is defined herein as time spent at a place and time when infective mosquitoes are biting.

  • Exposure rates are defined as the expected number of infective bites, per person, per day, or the daily entomological inoculation rate (dEIR).

Infection

  • The true prevalence of infection is the fraction of people who are infected with parasites. For historical reasons, we call this the parasite rate (PR).

  • The apparent PR is the fraction who are found to be infected by light microscopy (LM), by rapid diagnostic test (RDT), or by PCR.

  • The true and apparent PR vary with respect to age

    • Humans are born uninfected, so the PR rises with age.

    • Exposure to malaria tends to vary by age.

    • Immunity is acquired with age and exposure, reducing parasite densities and detection.

    • Drug taking probably varies with age.

  • The true and apparent PR vary with respect to sex

Scaling

We start with the simplest model in malaria, called the SIS compartment model. The relationship between the EIR and the PR is modified by several factors, including:

  • Drug taking with full compliance, cures infections and produces a brief period of chemoprotection. Compliance is, however, a sticky wicket.

  • Heterogeneous exposure:

    • Environmental heterogeneity describes the distribution of bites, per person.

    • Heterogeneous Biting, or frailties in exposure are handled through stratification, including heterogeneous biting by age, \(a\). Frailties, or differences in exposure by age and other factors, are handled through stratification – we assign biting weights.

  • Seasonality - The average EIR (aEIR) varies with the PR, but the dEIR is highly seasonal, and so is the PfPR. The timing of a survey can affect the relationship between the dEIR

  • Travel - The relationship between the dEIR and the PR by age is masked by travel malaria [1].

SIS

Here, we look at Ross’s model:

\[\frac{dX}{dt} = bE(H-X) - rX\] In the following, we plot with values of \(r \in \left\{1/100, 1/180, 1/220\right\}.\)

F_eir0 = function(t, pars){0*t+1}
F_eir1 = function(t, pars){(1.05 + sin(2*pi*t/365))}
F_eir2 = function(t, pars){F_eir1(t, pars)^2}
sis = xde_setup_cohort("sis", F_eir0, Xname = "SIS")
xde_scaling_eir(sis, 25) -> sis
sis0 <- sis
sis0$Xpar$r <- 1/100
xde_scaling_eir(sis0, 25) -> sis0
sis1 <- sis
sis1$Xpar$r <- 1/220
xde_scaling_eir(sis1, 25) -> sis1
with(sis$eirpr, plot(aeir, pr, type = "l", log = "x", xaxt= "n", xlab = "aEIR", ylab = "PR"))
axis(1, 10^(-1:3), c(0.1, 1, 10, 100, 1000))
with(sis0$eirpr, lines(aeir, pr, lty=2)) 
with(sis1$eirpr, lines(aeir, pr, lty=2))

Drug Taking

Drug taking is handled differently in every model (\(\cal X\)). Here, we explore the relationship with the model SIP.

plot(sis$eirpr$aeir, sis$eirpr$pr, type = "l", log = "x", xaxt= "n", xlab = "aEIR", ylab = "PR")
axis(1, 10^(-1:3), c(0.1, 1, 10, 100, 1000))

Heterogeneity

\(\oplus\)

A pair of studies of exposure to malaria across three sites in Uganda made a distinction between three components of heterogeneous exposure [2,3]: seasonality; heterogeneous biting or frailties in exposure; and environmental heterogeneity. In these two, we show how `exDE

Environmental Heterogeneity

Environmental Heterogeneity is handled through a function that converts the EIR into the FoI, \(h=F_h(E)\). As part of that function, mean biting can have a distribution which we incorporate through a function, \(F_h\) that captures environmental heterogeneity. Each model, \(d {\cal X}/ dt\), must supply a function to compute the probability of infection per infectious bite.

sis2 <- setup_exposure_nb(sis, 1/50)
xde_scaling_eir(sis2, 25) -> sis2
with(sis$eirpr, plot(aeir, pr, type = "l", log = "x", xaxt= "n", xlab = "aEIR", ylab = "PR"))
axis(1, 10^(-1:3), c(0.1, 1, 10, 100, 1000))
with(sis2$eirpr, lines(aeir, pr, col = "darkorange"))

Travel

We can sometimes overestimate local mosquito populations if there is exposure elsewhere. Some of this is handled through mobility in the TaR matrix and incorporated into \(\beta\). Malaria acquired through travel, \(\delta(t)\), is handled separately [1].

sis4 <- setup_travel_foi(sis, delta_scale = 1/5/365)
xde_scaling_eir(sis4, 25) -> sis4
with(sis$eirpr, plot(aeir, pr, type = "l", log = "x", xaxt= "n", xlab = "aEIR", ylab = "PR"))
axis(1, 10^(-1:3), c(0.1, 1, 10, 100, 1000))
with(sis4$eirpr, lines(aeir, pr, col = "darkgreen"))

Interactions

Summary

This figure summarizes the basic concepts:

  1. There is process uncertainty.

  2. The relationship is modified by drug taking, heterogeneous exposure, seasonality and travel.

  3. When these effects are combined, the effect size can be quite large.

Chron.Ann.Bib

Some important papers that got us here:

  • In 1933: Davey & Gordon publish a report on infective biting densities and plot the PR by age for two different populations where the EIR had been estimated [4].

  • In 1950: Macdonald took a critical look at the relationship between the EIR and the infant conversion rate [5]. He examined several papers, including the 1933 study by Davey & Gordon [4].

  • In 1997, a study by Woolhouse, et al., collected data from studies of several infectious diseases – including malaria – that documented heterogeneous exposure [6].

  • In 2004, Tom Smith looked at several studies that had examined the relationship between exposure and infection [7]. In 2006, as part of the set of papers that calibrated OpenMalaria looked at the relationship between the EIR and the FoI [8].

  • In 2005, Smith DL, et al., examined the relationship between the EIR and the PR, including some models with heterogeneous exposure [9]. The model used a database that had been developed by others describing paired estimates of the EIR and the PR [10,11].

  • In 2006, in a rebuttal to Smith DL, et al. (2005), Filion et al. argued that the same patterns we had attributed to heterogeneous exposure could be explained by pre-erythrocytic immunity [12].

  • In 2007, in a rebuttal to Smith DL, et al. (2005), Filion et al. argued that the same patterns we had attributed to heterogeneous exposure could be explained by pre-erythrocytic immunity [12].

  • In 2010, partly in response to Fillion Smith DL, et al. reviewed the relationship between the EIR and the FOI [13]. We used a functional form proposed by Filion et al. (2006), but we argued that the preponderance of evidence argues against pre-erythrocytic immunity. et al. 

  • 2015: Penny et al re-examined the relationship between the EIR and the PR [14] in two ways: first, we did age-correction on the PfPR data using the algorithm from our 2007 paper; and second we did a correction for the EIR trapping method.

  • 2018: Cooper et al looked at data from three sites in Uganda quantifying heterogeneity in transmission, parsing effects of seasonality, heterogeneous biting (i.e. frailties), and environmental heterogeneity [2,3]

  • 2019: Guerra et al examine the association between travel and malaria prevalence [1]

Caveats

  1. One source of heterogeneity in the relationship between the EIR and either the FOI or the PR is human mobility. The EIR measured here does not reflect the average level of exposure experienced by people living here. In some cases, travel can play an outsized role [Guerra, C. A. et al. Human mobility patterns and malaria importation on Bioko Island. Nat. Commun. 10, 2332 (2019)]. Here, we model the relationship between the local EIR and the PR.

  2. Estimates of the EIR vary by method before [Kilama, M. et al. Estimating the annual entomological inoculation rate for Plasmodium falciparum transmitted by Anopheles gambiae s.l. using three sampling methods in three sites in Uganda. Malar. J. 13, 111 (2014)] and after control.[Musiime, A. K. et al. Impact of vector control interventions on malaria transmission intensity, outdoor vector biting rates and Anopheles mosquito species composition in Tororo, Uganda. Malar. J. 18, 445 (2019)]

  3. Potential biases in the EIR estimates because of poor study designs.

  4. Problems with counting zero sporozoite positive mosquitoes.

Data and Benchmarking

Duration of an untreated infection without further exposure

  • In 1950 [Macdonald, G. The analysis of malaria parasite rates in infants. Trop. Dis. Bull. 47, 915–938 (1950)], Macdonald used data from a paper by Earle, et al. describing pararasitemia in a cohort of untreated children [Earle, W. C., Pérez, M., del Río, J. & Arzola, C. Observations on the Course of Naturally Acquired Malaria in Puerto Rico. PR J. Public Health Trop. Med. 14, 391–406 (1939)]. The data, replotted by Macdonald as Figure 1 and Table 1, come from Table 3 of Earle. In 1962, Earle provided the data in more granular form [Earle, W. C. The course of naturally acquired malaria. WHO/Mal/333 (Feb 7, 1962) https://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/64925/WHO_Mal_333.pdf]. Macdonald fit the curve to data. He found that after the first 31 days in which no one lost any infection, an exponential curve fit the data reasonably well with a decay rate of \(0.0048\), or an average of aboug 208 days. Having reread Earle’s paper, it’s not at all clear that new infections were not occurring.

  • The malariatherapy data.

  • In 1964, Macdonald and Goekel summarized data describing declines in the PR after interventions.

  • Nankabirwa, J. I. et al. Persistent Parasitemia Despite Dramatic Reduction in Malaria Incidence After 3 Rounds of Indoor Residual Spraying in Tororo, Uganda. J. Infect. Dis. 219, 1104–1111 (2019)

  • Bekessy, A., Molineaux, L. & Storey, J. Estimation of incidence and recovery rates of Plasmodium falciparum parasitaemia from longitudinal data. Bull. World Health Organ. 54, 685–693 (1976)

Cross-sectional EIR vs. PR

Disease and Anti-malarial Drugs

  • Rodriguez-Barraquer, I. et al. Quantification of anti-parasite and anti-disease immunity to malaria as a function of age and exposure. Elife 7, e35832 (2018)

  • This paper shows a rise in the attack rates with age, extreme heterogeneity in monthly attack rates (which were starkly different for rural and urban populations), and a nearly linear decline in the risk of malaria given infection.[Rodriguez-Barraquer, I. et al. Quantifying heterogeneous malaria exposure and clinical protection in a cohort of Ugandan children. J. Infect. Dis. 214, 1072–1080 (2016)]
